{"hitCount": 1, "request": {"cursorMark": "*", "pageSize": 1, "queryString": "DOI:\"10.3109/03639041003695071\"", "resultType": "core", "sort": "", "synonym": false}, "resultList": {"result": [{"abstractText": "<h4>Methods</h4>The thermodynamic, eutectic, and crystalline properties of ibuprofen and ketoprofen binary mixtures were investigated using differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) and X-ray powder diffractometry (XRPD).<h4>Results</h4>The DSC studies showed that melting point (61 degrees C), enthalpy (11.3 kJ/mol), and entropy of fusion (33.7 J/K/mol) of the binary eutectic were significantly lower than those of the individual anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs). Due to the melting-point depression and enhanced skin lipid solubility, the steady-state flux of ibuprofen and ketoprofen from preparations of the binary eutectic increased as compared to pure NSAIDs using shed snakeskin as a model membrane. The NSAID membrane flux values were calculated by flux ratio equations based on drug thermodynamic data, and compared to experimental values obtained from permeation studies.<h4>Conclusion</h4>The proposed flux ratio equations correctly predicted flux increase.", "affiliation": "Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Arnold & Marie Schwartz College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences, Long Island University, Brooklyn, NY, USA.", "authMan": "N", "authorList": {"author": [{"authorAffiliationDetailsList": {"authorAffiliation": [{"affiliation": "Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Arnold & Marie Schwartz College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences, Long Island University, Brooklyn, NY, USA."}]}, "firstName": "Xudong", "fullName": "Yuan X", "initials": "X", "lastName": "Yuan"}, {"firstName": "Anthony Cesare", "fullName": "Capomacchia AC", "initials": "AC", "lastName": "Capomacchia"}]}, "authorString": "Yuan X, Capomacchia AC.", "chemicalList": {"chemical": [{"name": "Anti-Inflammatory Agents, Non-Steroidal", "registryNumber": "0"}, {"name": "Drug Combinations", "registryNumbe